  <a href="#1" id="1">
   World leaders from President Bush to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev today, 12/15/1989, praised Andrei D. Sakharov as a tremendous force for freedom.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The 68-year-old scientist and human rights activist died Thursday, 12/14/1989, of an apparent heart attack.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   The Soviet Congress stood for a minute of silence for their colleague, once considered a national hero for discovering the Soviet hydrogen bomb but later reviled by Kremlin leadership for his uncompromising stands for human freedom.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Gorbachev, who freed the physicist from seven years of internal exile, called Sakharov a "man of conviction and sincerity".
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   "It's a great loss," Gorbachev said.
  </a>
